        <h3>Describing the information that is sent back to the form from the checkLastName() function and provide an explanation for the reason behind it.</h3>
        <p>
            The checkLastName() function is responsible for validating the last name input field in the addEmployee.html
            form. It performs the following actions:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                If the user inserts any non-alphabetic characters (characters other than letters) in the last name
                field, the function triggers an alert with an appropriate error message. It sets the focus back to the
                last name input box to draw the user's attention to the error. Finally, it returns false to indicate
                that there is an error in the form submission.
            </li>
            <li>
                If the user inserts only alphabetic characters in the last name field, the function does not trigger any
                alerts. It simply returns true, indicating that the form submission is valid and can proceed.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            This validation is important to ensure that the last name field contains only valid alphabetic characters.
            By returning false in case of an error, we prevent the form from being submitted and prompt the user to
            correct their input. Conversely, returning true allows the form to be submitted when the last name field
            contains valid data.
        </p>
